# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The Auger effect is an electronic process at the heart of AES resulting from the inter- and intrastate transitions of electrons in an excited atom.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] When an atom is probed by an external mechanism, such as a photon or a beam of electrons with energies in the range of several eV to 50 keV, a core state electron can be removed leaving behind a hole.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] As this is an unstable state, the core hole can be filled by an outer shell electron, whereby the electron moving to the lower energy level loses an amount of energy equal to the difference in orbital energies.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The transition energy can be coupled to a second outer shell electron, which will be emitted from the atom if the transferred energy is greater than the orbital binding energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] where $E_{\text{Core State}}$ , $E_{B}$ , $E_{C}'$ are respectively the core level, first outer shell, and second outer shell electron binding energies (measured from the vacuum level) which are taken to be positive.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The apostrophe (tic) denotes a slight modification to the binding energy of the outer shell electrons due to the ionized nature of the atom; often, however, this energy modification is ignored in order to ease calculations.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Since orbital energies are unique to an atom of a specific element, analysis of the ejected electrons can yield information about the chemical composition of a surface.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Figure 1 illustrates two schematic views of the Auger process.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The types of state-to-state transitions available to electrons during an Auger event are dependent on several factors, ranging from initial excitation energy to relative interaction rates, yet are often dominated by a few characteristic transitions.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Because of the interaction between an electron's spin and orbital angular momentum (spin-orbit coupling) and the concomitant energy level splitting for various shells in an atom, there are a variety of transition pathways for filling a core hole.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Energy levels are labeled using a number of different schemes such as the j-j coupling method for heavy elements (*Z* ≥ 75), the Russell–Saunders L-S method for lighter elements (*Z* < 20), and a combination of both for intermediate elements.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The j-j coupling method, which is historically linked to X-ray notation, is almost always used to denote Auger transitions.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Thus for a $KL_{1}L_{2,3}$ transition, K represents the core level hole, $L_{1}$ the relaxing electron's initial state, and $L_{2,3}$ the emitted electron's initial energy state.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Figure 1(b) illustrates this transition with the corresponding spectroscopic notation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The energy level of the core hole will often determine which transition types will be favored.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] *K*, transitions can occur from the L levels, giving rise to strong KLL type peaks in an Auger spectrum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Higher level transitions can also occur, but are less probable.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] For multi-level shells, transitions are available from higher energy orbitals (different *n, ℓ* quantum numbers) or energy levels within the same shell (same *n*, different *ℓ* number).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The result are transitions of the type LMM and KLL along with faster Coster–Kronig transitions such as LLM.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] While Coster–Kronig transitions are faster, they are also less energetic and thus harder to locate on an Auger spectrum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] As the atomic number Z increases, so too does the number of potential Auger transitions.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The strongest electron–electron interactions are between levels that are close together, giving rise to characteristic peaks in an Auger spectrum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] KLL and LMM peaks are some of the most commonly identified transitions during surface analysis.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Finally, valence band electrons can also fill core holes or be emitted during KVV-type transitions.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Several models, both phenomenological and analytical, have been developed to describe the energetics of Auger transitions.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] $E_{i}(Z)$ are the binding energies of the i th level in element of atomic number *Z* and $E_{i}(Z+1)$ are the energies of the same levels in the next element up in the periodic table.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] where $F(BC:x)$ is the energy of interaction between the *B* and *C* level holes in a final atomic state *x* and the *R'*s represent intra- and extra-atomic transition energies accounting for electronic screening.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Auger electron energies can be calculated based on measured values of the various $E_{i}$ and compared to peaks in the secondary electron spectrum in order to identify chemical species.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] This technique has been used to compile several reference databases used for analysis in current AES setups.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Surface sensitivity in AES arises from the fact that emitted electrons usually have energies ranging from 50 eV to 3 keV and at these values, electrons have a short mean free path in a solid.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The escape depth of electrons is therefore localized to within a few nanometers of the target surface, giving AES an extreme sensitivity to surface species.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Because of the low energy of Auger electrons, most AES setups are run under ultra-high vacuum (UHV) conditions.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Such measures prevent electron scattering off of residual gas atoms as well as the formation of a thin "gas (adsorbate) layer" on the surface of the specimen, which degrades analytical performance.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] A typical AES setup is shown schematically in figure 2.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] In this configuration, focused electrons are incident on a sample and emitted electrons are deflected into a cylindrical mirror analyzer (CMA).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] In the detection unit, Auger electrons are multiplied and the signal sent to data processing electronics.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Collected Auger electrons are plotted as a function of energy against the broad secondary electron background spectrum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The detection unit and data processing electronics are collectively referred to as the electron energy analyzer.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Since the intensity of the Auger peaks may be small compared to the noise level of the background, AES is often run in a derivative mode that serves to highlight the peaks by modulating the electron collection current via a small applied AC voltage.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Since this $\Delta V=k\sin(\omega t)$ , the collection current becomes $I(V+k\sin(\omega t))$ .
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Using the setup in figure 2, detecting the signal at frequency ω will give a value for $I'$ or ${\frac {dN}{dE}}$ .
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Plotting in derivative mode also emphasizes Auger fine structure, which appear as small secondary peaks surrounding the primary Auger peak.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] These secondary peaks, not to be confused with high energy satellites, which are discussed later, arise from the presence of the same element in multiple different chemical states on a surface (i.e.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Adsorbate layers) or from relaxation transitions involving valence band electrons of the substrate.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Figure 3 illustrates a derivative spectrum from a copper nitride film clearly showing the Auger peaks.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The peak in derivative mode is not the true Auger peak, but rather the point of maximum slope of *N(E)*, but this concern is usually ignored.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Semi-quantitative compositional and element analysis of a sample using AES is dependent on measuring the yield of Auger electrons during a probing event.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Electron yield, in turn, depends on several critical parameters such as electron-impact cross-section and fluorescence yield.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Since the Auger effect is not the only mechanism available for atomic relaxation, there is a competition between radiative and non-radiative decay processes to be the primary de-excitation pathway.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The total transition rate, ω, is a sum of the non-radiative (Auger) and radiative (photon emission) processes.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] where $W_{X}$ is the X-ray transition probability and $W_{A}$ is the Auger transition probability.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Attempts to relate the fluorescence and Auger yields to atomic number have resulted in plots similar to figure 4.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] A clear transition from electron to photon emission is evident in this chart for increasing atomic number.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] For heavier elements, x-ray yield becomes greater than Auger yield, indicating an increased difficulty in measuring the Auger peaks for large Z-values.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Conversely, AES is sensitive to the lighter elements, and unlike X-ray fluorescence, Auger peaks can be detected for elements as light as lithium (*Z* = 3).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Lithium represents the lower limit for AES sensitivity since the Auger effect is a "three state" event necessitating at least three electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Neither H nor He can be detected with this technique.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] For K-level based transitions, Auger effects are dominant for *Z* < 15 while for L- and M-level transitions, AES data can be measured for *Z* ≤ 50.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The yield limits effectively prescribe a cutoff for AES sensitivity, but complex techniques can be utilized to identify heavier elements, such as uranium and americium, using the Auger effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Another critical quantity that determines yield of Auger electrons at a detector is the electron impact cross-section.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] with *b* acting as a scaling factor between 0.25 and 0.35, and *C* a function of the primary electron beam energy, $E_{p}$ .
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] where α is the angle to the surface normal of the incident electron beam; *rm* can be established empirically and encompasses electron interactions with the matrix such as ionization due to backscattered electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Here *Nx* is the number of *x* atoms per volume, λ the electron escape depth, θ the analyzer angle, *T* the transmission of the analyzer, *I(t)* the electron excitation flux at depth *t*, dΩ the solid angle, and δt is the thickness of the layer being probed.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Encompassed in these terms, especially the Auger yield, which is related to the transition probability, is the quantum mechanical overlap of the initial and final state wave functions.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Precise expressions for the transition probability, based on first-order perturbation Hamiltonians, can be found in Thompson and Baker.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Often, all of these terms are not known, so most analyses compare measured yields with external standards of known composition.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Ratios of the acquired data to standards can eliminate common terms, especially experimental setup characteristics and material parameters, and can be used to determine element composition.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Comparison techniques work best for samples of homogeneous binary materials or uniform surface layers, while elemental identification is best obtained from comparison of pure samples.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] There are a number of electron microscopes that have been specifically designed for use in Auger spectroscopy; these are termed scanning Auger microscopes (SAMs) and can produce high resolution, spatially resolved chemical images.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] SAM images are obtained by stepping a focused electron beam across a sample surface and measuring the intensity of the Auger peak above the background of scattered electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The intensity map is correlated to a gray scale on a monitor with whiter areas corresponding to higher element concentration.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] In addition, sputtering is sometimes used with Auger spectroscopy to perform depth profiling experiments.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Sputtering removes thin outer layers of a surface so that AES can be used to determine the underlying composition.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Depth profiles are shown as either Auger peak height vs. sputter time or atomic concentration vs. depth.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Precise depth milling through sputtering has made profiling an invaluable technique for chemical analysis of nanostructured materials and thin films.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] AES is also used extensively as an evaluation tool on and off fab lines in the microelectronics industry, while the versatility and sensitivity of the Auger process makes it a standard analytical tool in research labs.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Theoretically, Auger spectra can also be utilized to distinguish between protonation states.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] When a molecule is protonated or deprotonated, the geometry and electronic structure is changed, and AES spectra reflect this.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] In general, as a molecule becomes more protonated, the ionization potentials increase and the kinetic energy of the emitted outer shell electrons decreases.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Despite the advantages of high spatial resolution and precise chemical sensitivity attributed to AES, there are several factors that can limit the applicability of this technique, especially when evaluating solid specimens.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] One of the most common limitations encountered with Auger spectroscopy are charging effects in non-conducting samples.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Charging results when the number of secondary electrons leaving the sample is different from the number of incident electrons, giving rise to a net positive or negative electric charge at the surface.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Both positive and negative surface charges severely alter the yield of electrons emitted from the sample and hence distort the measured Auger peaks.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] To complicate matters, neutralization methods employed in other surface analysis techniques, such as secondary ion mass spectrometry (SIMS), are not applicable to AES, as these methods usually involve surface bombardment with either electrons or ions (i.e. flood gun).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Several processes have been developed to combat the issue of charging, though none of them is ideal and still make quantification of AES data difficult.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] One such technique involves depositing conductive pads near the analysis area to minimize regional charging.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] However, this type of approach limits SAM applications as well as the amount of sample material available for probing.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] A related technique involves thinning or "dimpling" a non-conductive layer with Ar+ ions and then mounting the sample to a conductive backing prior to AES.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] This method has been debated, with claims that the thinning process leaves elemental artifacts on a surface and/or creates damaged layers that distort bonding and promote chemical mixing in the sample.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] As a result, the compositional AES data is considered suspect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The most common setup to minimize charging effects includes use of a glancing angle (~10°) electron beam and a carefully tuned bombarding energy (between 1.5 keV and 3 keV).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Control of both the angle and energy can subtly alter the number of emitted electrons vis-à-vis the incident electrons and thereby reduce or altogether eliminate sample charging.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] In addition to charging effects, AES data can be obscured by the presence of characteristic energy losses in a sample and higher order atomic ionization events.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Electrons ejected from a solid will generally undergo multiple scattering events and lose energy in the form of collective electron density oscillations called plasmons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] If plasmon losses have energies near that of an Auger peak, the less intense Auger process may become dwarfed by the plasmon peak.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] As Auger spectra are normally weak and spread over many eV of energy, they are difficult to extract from the background and in the presence of plasmon losses; deconvolution of the two peaks becomes extremely difficult.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] For such spectra, additional analysis through chemical sensitive surface techniques like x-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) is often required to disentangle the peaks.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Sometimes an Auger spectrum can also exhibit "satellite" peaks at well-defined off-set energies from the parent peak.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Origin of the satellites is usually attributed to multiple ionization events in an atom or ionization cascades in which a series of electrons is emitted as relaxation occurs for core holes of multiple levels.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] The presence of satellites can distort the true Auger peak and/or small peak shift information due to chemical bonding at the surface.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Several studies have been undertaken to further quantify satellite peaks.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] Despite these sometimes substantial drawbacks, Auger electron spectroscopy is a widely used surface analysis technique that has been successfully applied to many diverse fields ranging from gas phase chemistry to nanostructure characterization.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] A new class of high-resolving electrostatic energy analyzers, face-field analyzers (FFA) can be used for remote electron spectroscopy of distant surfaces or surfaces with large roughness or even with deep dimples.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] These instruments are designed as if to be specifically used in combined scanning electron microscopes (SEMs).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/auger-electron-spectroscopy] "FFA" in principle have no perceptible end-fields, which usually distort focusing in most of analysers known, for example, well known CMA.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] All other non-valence electrons for an atom of that element are considered core electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] A more complex explanation of the difference between core and valence electrons can be described with atomic orbital theory.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] In atoms with a single electron the energy of an orbital is determined exclusively by the principal quantum number *n*.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The *n* = 1 orbital has the lowest possible energy in the atom.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] For large *n*, the energy increases so much that the electron can easily escape from the atom.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] In single electron atoms, all energy levels with the same principle quantum number are degenerate, and have the same energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] In atoms with more than one electron, the energy of an electron depends not only on the properties of the orbital it resides in, but also on its interactions with the other electrons in other orbitals.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] This requires consideration of the *ℓ* quantum number.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Higher values of *ℓ* are associated with higher values of energy; for instance, the 2p state is higher than the 2s state.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] When *ℓ* = 2, the increase in energy of the orbital becomes large enough to push the energy of orbital above the energy of the s-orbital in the next higher shell; when *ℓ* = 3 the energy is pushed into the shell two steps higher.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The filling of the 3d orbitals does not occur until the 4s orbitals have been filled.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Thus, in atoms of higher atomic number, the *ℓ* of electrons becomes more and more of a determining factor in their energy, and the principal quantum numbers *n* of electrons becomes less and less important in their energy placement.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The energy sequence of the first 35 subshells (e.g., 1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, etc.) is given in the following table [not shown?].
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Each cell represents a subshell with *n* and *ℓ* given by its row and column indices, respectively.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The number in the cell is the subshell's position in the sequence.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] See the periodic table below, organized by subshells.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The atomic core refers to the central part of the atom excluding the valence electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The atomic core has a positive electric charge called the **core charge** and is the effective nuclear charge experienced by an outer shell electron.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] In other words, core charge is an expression of the attractive force experienced by the valence electrons to the core of an atom which takes into account the shielding effect of core electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Core charge can be calculated by taking the number of protons in the nucleus minus the number of core electrons, also called inner shell electrons, and is always a positive value in neutral atoms.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The mass of the core is almost equal to the mass of the atom.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The atomic core can be considered spherically symmetric with sufficient accuracy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The core radius is at least three times smaller than the radius of the corresponding atom (if we calculate the radii by the same methods).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] For heavy atoms, the core radius grows slightly with increasing number of electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The radius of the core of the heaviest naturally occurring element - uranium - is comparable to the radius of a lithium atom, although the latter has only three electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Chemical methods cannot separate the electrons of the core from the atom.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] When ionized by flame or ultraviolet radiation, atomic cores, as a rule, also remain intact.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Core charge is a convenient way of explaining trends in the periodic table.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Since the core charge increases as you move across a row of the periodic table, the outer-shell electrons are pulled more and more strongly towards the nucleus and the atomic radius decreases.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] This can be used to explain a number of periodic trends such as atomic radius, first ionization energy (IE), electronegativity, and oxidizing.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Core charge can also be calculated as 'atomic number' minus 'all electrons except those in the outer shell'.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] A core charge is the net charge of a nucleus, considering the completed shells of electrons to act as a 'shield.' As a core charge increases, the valence electrons are more strongly attracted to the nucleus, and the atomic radius decreases across the period.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] For elements with high atomic number *Z*, relativistic effects can be observed for core electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The velocities of core s electrons reach relativistic momentum which leads to contraction of 6s orbitals relative to 5d orbitals.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Physical properties affected by these relativistic effects include lowered melting temperature of mercury and the observed golden colour of gold and caesium due to narrowing of energy gap.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Gold appears yellow because it absorbs blue light more than it absorbs other visible wavelengths of light and so reflects back yellow-toned light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] A core electron can be removed from its core-level upon absorption of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] This will either excite the electron to an empty valence shell or cause it to be emitted as a *photoelectron* due to the photoelectric effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The resulting atom will have an empty space in the core electron shell, often referred to as a *core-hole*.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] It is in a metastable state and will decay within 10−15 s, releasing the excess energy via X-ray fluorescence (as a characteristic X-ray) or by the Auger effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Detection of the energy emitted by a valence electron falling into a lower-energy orbital provides useful information on the electronic and local lattice structures of a material.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Although most of the time this energy is released in the form of a *photon*, the energy can also be transferred to another electron, which is ejected from the atom.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] This second ejected electron is called an Auger electron and this process of electronic transition with indirect radiation emission is known as the Auger effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] Every atom except hydrogen has core-level electrons with well-defined binding energies.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] It is therefore possible to select an element to probe by tuning the X-ray energy to the appropriate absorption edge.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/core-electron] The spectra of the radiation emitted can be used to determine the elemental composition of a material.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] The **inelastic mean free path** (**IMFP**) is an index of how far an electron on average travels through a solid before losing energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] If a monochromatic, primary beam of electrons is incident on a solid surface, the majority of incident electrons lose their energy because they interact strongly with matter, leading to plasmon excitation, electron-hole pair formation, and vibrational excitation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] The intensity of the primary electrons, *I*0, is damped as a function of the distance, d, into the solid.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] where *I*(*d*) is the intensity after the primary electron beam has traveled through the solid to a distance d.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] The parameter λ(*E*), termed the inelastic mean free path (IMFP), is defined as the distance an electron beam can travel before its intensity decays to 1/e of its initial value.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] The inelastic mean free path of electrons can roughly be described by a universal curve that is the same for all materials.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] The knowledge of the IMFP is indispensable for several electron spectroscopy and microscopy measurements.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Following, the IMFP is employed to calculate the effective attenuation length (EAL), the mean escape depth (MED) and the information depth (ID).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Besides, one can utilize the IMFP to make matrix corrections for the relative sensitivity factor in quantitative surface analysis.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Moreover, the IMFP is an important parameter in Monte Carlo simulations of photoelectron transport in matter.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Calculations of the IMFP are mostly based on the algorithm (full Penn algorithm, FPA) developed by Penn, experimental optical constants or calculated optical data (for compounds).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] The FPA considers an inelastic scattering event and the dependence of the energy-loss function (EFL) on momentum transfer which describes the probability for inelastic scattering as a function of momentum transfer.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] To measure the IMFP, one well known method is elastic-peak electron spectroscopy (EPES).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] This method measures the intensity of elastically backscattered electrons with a certain energy from a sample material in a certain direction.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Applying a similar technique to materials whose IMFP is known, the measurements are compared with the results from the Monte Carlo simulations under the same conditions.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Thus, one obtains the IMFP of a certain material in a certain energy spectrum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] EPES measurements show a root-mean-square (RMS) difference between 12% and 17% from the theoretical expected values.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Calculated and experimental results show higher agreement for higher energies.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] For electron energies in the range 30 keV – 1 MeV, IMFP can be directly measured by electron energy loss spectroscopy inside a transmission electron microscope, provided the sample thickness is known.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Such measurements reveal that IMFP in elemental solids is not a smooth, but an oscillatory function of the atomic number.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] For energies below 100 eV, IMFP can be evaluated in high-energy secondary electron yield (SEY) experiments.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Therefore, the SEY for an arbitrary incident energy between 0.1 keV-10 keV is analyzed.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] According to these experiments, a Monte Carlo model can be used to simulate the SEYs and determine the IMFP below 100 eV.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] In general, solving this integral is quite challenging and only applies for energies above 100 eV.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Thus, (semi)empirical formulas were introduced to determine the IMFP.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] A first approach is to calculate the IMFP by an approximate form of the relativistic Bethe equation for inelastic scattering of electrons in matter.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Equation **2** calculates the IMFP and its dependence on the electron energy in condensed matter.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Here, the bandgap energy $E_{g}$ is given in eV.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Equation **2** an **3** are also known as the TTP-2M equations and are in general applicable for energies between 50 eV and 200 keV.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Neglecting a few materials (diamond, graphite, Cs, cubic-BN and hexagonal BN) that are not following these equations (due to deviations in $\beta$ ), the TTP-2M equations show precise agreement with the measurements.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Another approach based on Equation **2** to determine the IMFP is the S1 formula.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] with the Avogadro constant $N_{A}$ and the stoichiometric coefficients g and h describing binary compounds $G_{g}H_{h}$ .
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] with the atomic numbers $Z_{g}$ and $Z_{h}$ of the two constituents.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] This S1 formula shows higher agreement with measurements compared to Equation **2**.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Calculating the IMFP with either the TTP-2M formula or the S1 formula requires different knowledge of some parameters.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Applying the TTP-2M formula one needs to know M , $\rho$ and $N_{\nu }$ for conducting materials (and also $E_{g}$ for non-conductors).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Employing S1 formula, knowledge of the atomic number Z (average atomic number for compounds), M and $\rho$ is required for conductors.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] If non-conducting materials are considered, one also needs to know either $E_{g}$ or H .
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] An analytical formula for calculating the IMFP down to 50 eV was proposed in 2021.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] IMFP data can be collected from the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) Electron Inelastic-Mean-Free-Path Database or the NIST Database for the Simulation of Electron Spectra for Surface Analysis (SESSA).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] The data contains IMFPs determined by EPES for energies below 2 keV.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/inelastic-mean-free-path] Otherwise, IMFPs can be determined from the TPP-2M or the S1 formula.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The **photoelectric effect** is the emission of electrons from a material caused by electromagnetic radiation such as ultraviolet light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Electrons emitted in this manner are called **photoelectrons**.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The phenomenon is studied in condensed matter physics, solid state, and quantum chemistry to draw inferences about the properties of atoms, molecules and solids.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The effect has found use in electronic devices specialized for light detection and precisely timed electron emission.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The experimental results disagree with classical electromagnetism, which predicts that continuous light waves transfer energy to electrons, which would then be emitted when they accumulate enough energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] An alteration in the intensity of light would theoretically change the kinetic energy of the emitted electrons, with sufficiently dim light resulting in a delayed emission.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The experimental results instead show that electrons are dislodged only when the light exceeds a certain frequency—regardless of the light's intensity or duration of exposure.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Emission of conduction electrons from typical metals requires a few electron-volt (eV) light quanta, corresponding to short-wavelength visible or ultraviolet light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In extreme cases, emissions are induced with photons approaching zero energy, like in systems with negative electron affinity and the emission from excited states, or a few hundred keV photons for core electrons in elements with a high atomic number.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Study of the photoelectric effect led to important steps in understanding the quantum nature of light and electrons and influenced the formation of the concept of wave–particle duality.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Other phenomena where light affects the movement of electric charges include the photoconductive effect, the photovoltaic effect, and the photoelectrochemical effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The photons of a light beam have a characteristic energy, called photon energy, which is proportional to the frequency of the light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In the photoemission process, when an electron within some material absorbs the energy of a photon and acquires more energy than its binding energy, it is likely to be ejected.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] If the photon energy is too low, the electron is unable to escape the material.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Since an increase in the intensity of low-frequency light will only increase the number of low-energy photons, this change in intensity will not create any single photon with enough energy to dislodge an electron.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Moreover, the energy of the emitted electrons will not depend on the intensity of the incoming light of a given frequency, but only on the energy of the individual photons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] While free electrons can absorb any energy when irradiated as long as this is followed by an immediate re-emission, like in the Compton effect, in quantum systems all of the energy from one photon is absorbed—if the process is allowed by quantum mechanics—or none at all.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Part of the acquired energy is used to liberate the electron from its atomic binding, and the rest contributes to the electron's kinetic energy as a free particle.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Because electrons in a material occupy many different quantum states with different binding energies, and because they can sustain energy losses on their way out of the material, the emitted electrons will have a range of kinetic energies.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The electrons from the highest occupied states will have the highest kinetic energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In metals, those electrons will be emitted from the Fermi level.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] When the photoelectron is emitted into a solid rather than into a vacuum, the term *internal photoemission* is often used, and emission into a vacuum is distinguished as *external photoemission*.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Even though photoemission can occur from any material, it is most readily observed from metals and other conductors.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This is because the process produces a charge imbalance which, if not neutralized by current flow, results in the increasing potential barrier until the emission completely ceases.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The energy barrier to photoemission is usually increased by nonconductive oxide layers on metal surfaces, so most practical experiments and devices based on the photoelectric effect use clean metal surfaces in evacuated tubes.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Vacuum also helps observing the electrons since it prevents gases from impeding their flow between the electrodes.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Sunlight is an inconsistent and variable source of ultraviolet light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Cloud cover, ozone concentration, altitude, and surface reflection all alter the amount of UV.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Laboratory sources of UV are based on xenon arc lamps or, for more uniform but weaker light, fluorescent lamps.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] More specialized sources include ultraviolet lasers and synchrotron radiation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The classical setup to observe the photoelectric effect includes a light source, a set of filters to monochromatize the light, a vacuum tube transparent to ultraviolet light, an emitting electrode (E) exposed to the light, and a collector (C) whose voltage *V*C can be externally controlled.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] A positive external voltage is used to direct the photoemitted electrons onto the collector.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] If the frequency and the intensity of the incident radiation are fixed, the photoelectric current *I* increases with an increase in the positive voltage, as more and more electrons are directed onto the electrode.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] When no additional photoelectrons can be collected, the photoelectric current attains a saturation value.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This current can only increase with the increase of the intensity of light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] An increasing negative voltage prevents all but the highest-energy electrons from reaching the collector.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] When no current is observed through the tube, the negative voltage has reached the value that is high enough to slow down and stop the most energetic photoelectrons of kinetic energy *K*max.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This value of the retarding voltage is called the *stopping potential* or *cut off* potential *V*o.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Since the work done by the retarding potential in stopping the electron of charge *e* is *eV*o, the following must hold *eV*o = *K*max.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The current-voltage curve is sigmoidal, but its exact shape depends on the experimental geometry and the electrode material properties.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] For a given metal surface, there exists a certain minimum frequency of incident radiation below which no photoelectrons are emitted.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This frequency is called the *threshold frequency*.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Increasing the frequency of the incident beam increases the maximum kinetic energy of the emitted photoelectrons, and the stopping voltage has to increase.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The number of emitted electrons may also change because the probability that each photon results in an emitted electron is a function of photon energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] For a given metal and frequency of incident radiation, the rate at which photoelectrons are ejected is directly proportional to the intensity of the incident light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The time lag between the incidence of radiation and the emission of a photoelectron is very small, less than 10−9 second.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Angular distribution of the photoelectrons is highly dependent on polarization (the direction of the electric field) of the incident light, as well as the emitting material's quantum properties such as atomic and molecular orbital symmetries and the electronic band structure of crystalline solids.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In materials without macroscopic order, the distribution of electrons tends to peak in the direction of polarization of linearly polarized light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The experimental technique that can measure these distributions to infer the material's properties is angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In 1905, Albert Einstein proposed a theory of the photoelectric effect using a concept that light consists of tiny packets of energy known as photons or light quanta.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Each packet carries energy $h\nu$ that is proportional to the frequency $\nu$ of the corresponding electromagnetic wave.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The proportionality constant h has become known as the Planck constant.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] It is called the work function of the surface and is sometimes denoted $\Phi$ or $\varphi$ .
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Kinetic energy is positive, and $\nu >\nu _{o}$ is required for the photoelectric effect to occur.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The frequency $\nu _{o}$ is the threshold frequency for the given material.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Einstein's formula, however simple, explained all the phenomenology of the photoelectric effect, and had far-reaching consequences in the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Electrons that are bound in atoms, molecules and solids each occupy distinct states of well-defined binding energies.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] When light quanta deliver more than this amount of energy to an individual electron, the electron may be emitted into free space with excess (kinetic) energy that is $h\nu$ higher than the electron's binding energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The distribution of kinetic energies thus reflects the distribution of the binding energies of the electrons in the atomic, molecular or crystalline system: an electron emitted from the state at binding energy $E_{B}$ is found at kinetic energy $E_{k}=h\nu -E_{B}$ .
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This distribution is one of the main characteristics of the quantum system, and can be used for further studies in quantum chemistry and quantum physics.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The electronic properties of ordered, crystalline solids are determined by the distribution of the electronic states with respect to energy and momentum—the electronic band structure of the solid.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Theoretical models of photoemission from solids show that this distribution is, for the most part, preserved in the photoelectric effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Electron propagation to the surface in which some electrons may be scattered because of interactions with other constituents of the solid.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Electrons that originate deeper in the solid are much more likely to suffer collisions and emerge with altered energy and momentum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Their mean-free path is a universal curve dependent on electron's energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Electron escape through the surface barrier into free-electron-like states of the vacuum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In this step the electron loses energy in the amount of the *work function of the surface*, and suffers from the momentum loss in the direction perpendicular to the surface.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] There are cases where the three-step model fails to explain peculiarities of the photoelectron intensity distributions.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The more elaborate *one-step model* treats the effect as a coherent process of photoexcitation into the final state of a finite crystal for which the wave function is free-electron-like outside of the crystal, but has a decaying envelope inside.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In 1839, Alexandre Edmond Becquerel discovered the related photovoltaic effect while studying the effect of light on electrolytic cells.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Though not equivalent to the photoelectric effect, his work on photovoltaics was instrumental in showing a strong relationship between light and electronic properties of materials.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In 1873, Willoughby Smith discovered photoconductivity in selenium while testing the metal for its high resistance properties in conjunction with his work involving submarine telegraph cables.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Johann Elster (1854–1920) and Hans Geitel (1855–1923), students in Heidelberg, investigated the effects produced by light on electrified bodies and developed the first practical photoelectric cells that could be used to measure the intensity of light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The order of the metals for this effect was the same as in Volta's series for contact-electricity, the most electropositive metals giving the largest photo-electric effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In 1887, Heinrich Hertz observed the photoelectric effect and reported on the production and reception of electromagnetic waves.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The receiver in his apparatus consisted of a coil with a spark gap, where a spark would be seen upon detection of electromagnetic waves.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] He placed the apparatus in a darkened box to see the spark better.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] However, he noticed that the maximum spark length was reduced when inside the box.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] A glass panel that was placed between the source of electromagnetic waves and the receiver absorbed ultraviolet radiation that assisted the electrons in jumping across the gap.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] When removed, the spark length would increase.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] He observed no decrease in spark length when he replaced the glass with quartz, as quartz does not absorb UV radiation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The discoveries by Hertz led to a series of investigations by Wilhelm Hallwachs, Hoor, Augusto Righi and Aleksander Stoletov on the effect of light, and especially of ultraviolet light, on charged bodies.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Hallwachs connected a zinc plate to an electroscope.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] He allowed ultraviolet light to fall on a freshly cleaned zinc plate and observed that the zinc plate became uncharged if initially negatively charged, positively charged if initially uncharged, and more positively charged if initially positively charged.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] From these observations he concluded that some negatively charged particles were emitted by the zinc plate when exposed to ultraviolet light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] With regard to the *Hertz effect*, the researchers from the start showed the complexity of the phenomenon of photoelectric fatigue—the progressive diminution of the effect observed upon fresh metallic surfaces.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] According to Hallwachs, ozone played an important part in the phenomenon, and the emission was influenced by oxidation, humidity, and the degree of polishing of the surface.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] It was at the time unclear whether fatigue is absent in a vacuum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In the period from 1888 until 1891, a detailed analysis of the photoeffect was performed by Aleksandr Stoletov with results reported in six publications.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Stoletov invented a new experimental setup which was more suitable for a quantitative analysis of the photoeffect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] He discovered a direct proportionality between the intensity of light and the induced photoelectric current (the first law of photoeffect or Stoletov's law).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Many substances besides metals discharge negative electricity under the action of ultraviolet light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Knoblauch compiled a list of these substances.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Thomson investigated ultraviolet light in Crookes tubes.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Thomson deduced that the ejected particles, which he called corpuscles, were of the same nature as cathode rays.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] These particles later became known as the electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Thomson enclosed a metal plate (a cathode) in a vacuum tube, and exposed it to high-frequency radiation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] It was thought that the oscillating electromagnetic fields caused the atoms' field to resonate and, after reaching a certain amplitude, caused subatomic corpuscles to be emitted, and current to be detected.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The amount of this current varied with the intensity and color of the radiation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Larger radiation intensity or frequency would produce more current.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] During the years 1886–1902, Wilhelm Hallwachs and Philipp Lenard investigated the phenomenon of photoelectric emission in detail.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Lenard observed that a current flows through an evacuated glass tube enclosing two electrodes when ultraviolet radiation falls on one of them.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] As soon as ultraviolet radiation is stopped, the current also stops.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This initiated the concept of photoelectric emission.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The discovery of the ionization of gases by ultraviolet light was made by Philipp Lenard in 1900.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] As the effect was produced across several centimeters of air and yielded a greater number of positive ions than negative, it was natural to interpret the phenomenon, as J.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Thomson did, as a *Hertz effect* upon the particles present in the gas.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In 1902, Lenard observed that the energy of individual emitted electrons was independent of the applied light intensity.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This appeared to be at odds with Maxwell's wave theory of light, which predicted that the electron energy would be proportional to the intensity of the radiation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Lenard observed the variation in electron energy with light frequency using a powerful electric arc lamp which enabled him to investigate large changes in intensity.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] However, Lenard's results were qualitative rather than quantitative because of the difficulty in performing the experiments: the experiments needed to be done on freshly cut metal so that the pure metal was observed, but it oxidized in a matter of minutes even in the partial vacuums he used.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The current emitted by the surface was determined by the light's intensity, or brightness: doubling the intensity of the light doubled the number of electrons emitted from the surface.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Initial investigation of the photoelectric effect in gasses by Lenard were followed up by J.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Thomson and then more decisively by Frederic Palmer Jr.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The gas photoemission was studied and showed very different characteristics than those at first attributed to it by Lenard.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In 1900, while studying black-body radiation, the German physicist Max Planck suggested in his "On the Law of Distribution of Energy in the Normal Spectrum" paper that the energy carried by electromagnetic waves could only be released in *packets* of energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In 1905, Albert Einstein published a paper advancing the hypothesis that light energy is carried in discrete quantized packets to explain experimental data from the photoelectric effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Einstein theorized that the energy in each quantum of light was equal to the frequency of light multiplied by a constant, later called the Planck constant.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] A photon above a threshold frequency has the required energy to eject a single electron, creating the observed effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This was a step in the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Millikan's highly accurate measurements of the Planck constant from the photoelectric effect supported Einstein's model, even though a corpuscular theory of light was for Millikan, at the time, "quite unthinkable".
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Einstein was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics for "his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect", and Millikan was awarded the Nobel Prize in 1923 for "his work on the elementary charge of electricity and on the photoelectric effect".
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Albert Einstein's mathematical description of how the photoelectric effect was caused by absorption of quanta of light was in one of his Annus Mirabilis papers, named "On a Heuristic Viewpoint Concerning the Production and Transformation of Light".
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The paper proposed a simple description of *energy quanta*, and showed how they explained the blackbody radiation spectrum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] His explanation in terms of absorption of discrete quanta of light agreed with experimental results.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] It explained why the energy of photoelectrons was not dependent on incident light *intensity*.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This was a theoretical leap, but the concept was strongly resisted at first because it contradicted the wave theory of light that followed naturally from James Clerk Maxwell's equations of electromagnetism, and more generally, the assumption of infinite divisibility of energy in physical systems.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Einstein's work predicted that the energy of individual ejected electrons increases linearly with the frequency of the light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The precise relationship had not at that time been tested.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] By 1905 it was known that the energy of photoelectrons increases with increasing *frequency* of incident light and is independent of the *intensity* of the light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] However, the manner of the increase was not experimentally determined until 1914 when Millikan showed that Einstein's prediction was correct.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In 1937, the Bulgarian physicist Georgi Nadjakov discovered the *photoelectret state* in dielectrics.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The phenomenon is related to photoelectric effects in solids and later contributed to the physical basis of xerography.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The photoelectric effect helped to propel the then-emerging concept of wave–particle duality in the nature of light.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Light simultaneously possesses the characteristics of both waves and particles, each being manifested according to the circumstances.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The effect was impossible to understand in terms of the classical wave description of light, as the energy of the emitted electrons did not depend on the intensity of the incident radiation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Classical theory predicted that the electrons would 'gather up' energy over a period of time, and then be emitted.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The quantum of light was given its modern name by Gilbert N.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Lewis when he coined the term 'photon' in his letter "The Conservation of Photons" to *Nature* published in 18 December 1926.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Research in recent years on the photoelectric effect has been focused on measurements on emission time of photoelectrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] For long, it was believed that photoemission is an instantaneous process.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] However, a seminal role in this field was played by experimental techniques on attosecond generation of pulses of light for studies on electron dynamics, which was recognised through the 2023 Nobel Prize in physics to Pierre Agostini, Ferenc Krausz and Anne L'Huillier.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] For example, in 2010, it was discovered that electron emission takes 20 attoseconds and that photoemission is associated with complex multielectron correlations and is not a single-electron process.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In a more recent work in the context of tungsten, measurements on photoelectron emission indicated that around 100 attoseconds are required to liberate an electron.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In another research, the value was found to be 45 attoseconds.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] A broad consensus is emerging towards the fact that photoemission is not instantaneous and involves finite time.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The role of electric field in photoelectric effect has also been empirically studied and it was found that electromagnetic radiation with a specific orientation of electric field can excite electrons leading to enhanced emission in the Terahertz range.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] These are extremely light-sensitive vacuum tubes with a coated photocathode inside the envelope.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The photo cathode contains combinations of materials such as cesium, rubidium, and antimony specially selected to provide a low work function, so when illuminated even by very low levels of light, the photocathode readily releases electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] By means of a series of electrodes (dynodes) at ever-higher potentials, these electrons are accelerated and substantially increased in number through secondary emission to provide a readily detectable output current.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Photomultipliers are still commonly used wherever low levels of light must be detected.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Video camera tubes in the early days of television used the photoelectric effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] For example, Philo Farnsworth's "Image dissector" used a screen charged by the photoelectric effect to transform an optical image into a scanned electronic signal.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The distribution of electron energies is valuable for studying quantum properties of these systems.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] It can also be used to determine the elemental composition of the samples.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] For solids, the kinetic energy and emission angle distribution of the photoelectrons is measured for the complete determination of the electronic band structure in terms of the allowed binding energies and momenta of the electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Modern instruments for angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy are capable of measuring these quantities with a precision better than 1 meV and 0.1°.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Photoelectron spectroscopy measurements are usually performed in a high-vacuum environment, because the electrons would be scattered by gas molecules if they were present.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] However, some companies are now selling products that allow photoemission in air.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The light source can be a laser, a discharge tube, or a synchrotron radiation source.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The concentric hemispherical analyzer is a typical electron energy analyzer.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] It uses an electric field between two hemispheres to change (disperse) the trajectories of incident electrons depending on their kinetic energies.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Photons hitting a thin film of alkali metal or semiconductor material such as gallium arsenide in an image intensifier tube cause the ejection of photoelectrons due to the photoelectric effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] These are accelerated by an electrostatic field where they strike a phosphor coated screen, converting the electrons back into photons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Intensification of the signal is achieved either through acceleration of the electrons or by increasing the number of electrons through secondary emissions, such as with a micro-channel plate.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Sometimes a combination of both methods is used.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Additional kinetic energy is required to move an electron out of the conduction band and into the vacuum level.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This is known as the electron affinity of the photocathode and is another barrier to photoemission other than the forbidden band, explained by the band gap model.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Some materials such as gallium arsenide have an effective electron affinity that is below the level of the conduction band.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] In these materials, electrons that move to the conduction band all have sufficient energy to be emitted from the material, so the film that absorbs photons can be quite thick.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] These materials are known as negative electron affinity materials.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The photoelectric effect will cause spacecraft exposed to sunlight to develop a positive charge.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This can be a major problem, as other parts of the spacecraft are in shadow which will result in the spacecraft developing a negative charge from nearby plasmas.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The imbalance can discharge through delicate electrical components.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The static charge created by the photoelectric effect is self-limiting, because a higher charged object does not give up its electrons as easily as a lower charged object does.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Light from the Sun hitting lunar dust causes it to become positively charged from the photoelectric effect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The charged dust then repels itself and lifts off the surface of the Moon by electrostatic levitation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This manifests itself almost like an "atmosphere of dust", visible as a thin haze and blurring of distant features, and visible as a dim glow after the sun has set.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] This was first photographed by the Surveyor program probes in the 1960s, and most recently the Chang'e 3 rover observed dust deposition on lunar rocks as high as about 28 cm.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] It is thought that the smallest particles are repelled kilometers from the surface and that the particles move in "fountains" as they charge and discharge.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The probability of the photoelectric effect occurring is measured by the cross section of the interaction, which the atomic number of the target atom and photon energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Here *Z* is the atomic number and *n* is a number which varies between 4 and 5.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] The photoelectric effect rapidly decreases in significance in the gamma-ray region of the spectrum, with increasing photon energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] It is also more likely from elements with high atomic number.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Consequently, high-*Z* materials make good gamma-ray shields, which is the principal reason why lead (*Z* = 82) is preferred and most widely used.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] These cross-sections vary with the atomic number of the element that dominates the material and with the energy of the photons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] As photon energies increase above those of a materials K-edge the probability of photoelectric interactions decreases and Compton scattering begins to dominate.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/photoelectric-effect] Above photon energies of 1.022 MeV, pair production begins, increasing rapidly with photon energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] where *h* is the Planck constant, *ν* is the frequency of the ionizing light, and *I* is an ionization energy for the formation of a singly charged ion in either the ground state or an excited state.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] According to Koopmans' theorem, each such ionization energy may be identified with the energy of an occupied molecular orbital.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The ground-state ion is formed by removal of an electron from the highest occupied molecular orbital, while excited ions are formed by removal of an electron from a lower occupied orbital.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Before 1960, virtually all measurements of photoelectron kinetic energies were for electrons emitted from metals and other solid surfaces.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] In about 1956, Kai Siegbahn developed X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) for surface chemical analysis.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] This method uses x-ray sources to study energy levels of atomic core electrons, and at the time had an energy resolution of about 1 eV (electronvolt).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The ultraviolet photoelectron spectroscopy (UPS) was pioneered by Feodor I.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Petersburg (Leningrad) State University in Russia (USSR) in 1961 to study the photoelectron spectra of free molecules in the gas phase.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The early experiments used monochromatized radiation from a hydrogen discharge and a retarding potential analyzer to measure the photoelectron energies.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The PES was further developed by David W.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Turner, a physical chemist at Imperial College in London and then at Oxford University, in a series of publications from 1962 to 1967.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] As a photon source, he used a helium discharge lamp that emits a wavelength of 58.4 nm (corresponding to an energy of 21.2 eV) in the vacuum ultraviolet region.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] With this source, Turner's group obtained an energy resolution of 0.02 eV.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Turner referred to the method as "molecular photoelectron spectroscopy", now usually "ultraviolet photoelectron spectroscopy" or UPS.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] As compared to XPS, UPS is limited to energy levels of valence electrons, but measures them more accurately.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] After 1967, commercial UPS spectrometers became available.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] One of the latest commercial devices was the Perkin Elmer PS18.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] For the last twenty years, the systems have been homemade.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] One of the latest in progress – Phoenix II – is that of the laboratory of Pau, IPREM developed by Dr.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The UPS measures experimental molecular orbital energies for comparison with theoretical values from quantum chemistry, which was also extensively developed in the 1960s.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The photoelectron spectrum of a molecule contains a series of peaks each corresponding to one valence-region molecular orbital energy level.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Also, the high resolution allowed the observation of fine structure due to vibrational levels of the molecular ion, which facilitates the assignment of peaks to bonding, nonbonding or antibonding molecular orbitals.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The method was later extended to the study of solid surfaces where it is usually described as photoemission spectroscopy (PES).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] It is particularly sensitive to the surface region (to 10 nm depth), due to the short range of the emitted photoelectrons (compared to X-rays).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] It is therefore used to study adsorbed species and their binding to the surface, as well as their orientation on the surface.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] A useful result from characterization of solids by UPS is the determination of the work function of the material.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] An example of this determination is given by Park et al.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Briefly, the full width of the photoelectron spectrum (from the highest kinetic energy/lowest binding energy point to the low kinetic energy cutoff) is measured and subtracted from the photon energy of the exciting radiation, and the difference is the work function.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Often, the sample is electrically biased negative to separate the low energy cutoff from the spectrometer response.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/ultraviolet-photoelectron-spectroscopy] UPS has seen a considerable revival with the increasing availability of synchrotron light sources that provide a wide range of monochromatic photon energies.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Chemical states are inferred from the measurement of the kinetic energy and the number of the ejected electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] XPS requires high vacuum (residual gas pressure *p* ~ 10−6 Pa) or ultra-high vacuum (p < 10−7 Pa) conditions, although a current area of development is ambient-pressure XPS, in which samples are analyzed at pressures of a few tens of millibar.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] When laboratory X-ray sources are used, XPS easily detects all elements except hydrogen and helium.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The detection limit is in the parts per thousand range, but parts per million (ppm) are achievable with long collection times and concentration at top surface.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] XPS is routinely used to analyze inorganic compounds, metal alloys, polymers, elements, catalysts, glasses, ceramics, paints, papers, inks, woods, plant parts, make-up, teeth, bones, medical implants, bio-materials, coatings, viscous oils, glues, ion-modified materials and many others.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Somewhat less routinely XPS is used to analyze the hydrated forms of materials such as hydrogels and biological samples by freezing them in their hydrated state in an ultrapure environment, and allowing multilayers of ice to sublime away prior to analysis.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] where *E*binding is the binding energy of the electron measured relative to the sample Fermi level, *E*photon is the energy of the X-ray photons being used, *E*kinetic is the kinetic energy of the electron as measured by the instrument (spectrometer) and $\phi$ is a work function of spectrometer.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] This equation is essentially a conservation of energy equation.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The spectrometer work function term $\phi$ is a constant instrumental factor under the assumption that the sample and spectrometer have a common Fermi level, i.e., they are electrically connected, which is achieved by grounding the sample.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] In 1887, Heinrich Rudolf Hertz discovered but could not explain the photoelectric effect, which was later explained in 1905 by Albert Einstein (Nobel Prize in Physics 1921).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Two years after Einstein's publication, in 1907, P.D.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Innes experimented with a Röntgen tube, Helmholtz coils, a magnetic field hemisphere (an electron kinetic energy analyzer), and photographic plates, to record broad bands of emitted electrons as a function of velocity, in effect recording the first XPS spectrum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Other researchers, including Henry Moseley, Rawlinson and Robinson, independently performed various experiments to sort out the details in the broad bands.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] After WWII, Kai Siegbahn and his research group in Uppsala (Sweden) developed several significant improvements in the equipment, and in 1954 recorded the first high-energy-resolution XPS spectrum of cleaved sodium chloride (NaCl), revealing the potential of XPS.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] A few years later in 1967, Siegbahn published a comprehensive study of XPS, bringing instant recognition of the utility of XPS and also the first hard X-ray photoemission experiments, which he referred to as Electron Spectroscopy for Chemical Analysis (ESCA).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] In cooperation with Siegbahn, a small group of engineers (Mike Kelly, Charles Bryson, Lavier Faye, Robert Chaney) at Hewlett-Packard in the US, produced the first commercial monochromatic XPS instrument in 1969.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Siegbahn received the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1981, to acknowledge his extensive efforts to develop XPS into a useful analytical tool.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] In parallel with Siegbahn's work, David Turner at Imperial College London (and later at Oxford University) developed ultraviolet photoelectron spectroscopy (UPS) for molecular species using helium lamps.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] A typical XPS spectrum is a plot of the number of electrons detected at a specific binding energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Each element produces a set of characteristic XPS peaks.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] These peaks correspond to the electron configuration of the electrons within the atoms, e.g., 1*s*, 2*s*, 2*p*, 3*s*, etc.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The number of detected electrons in each peak is directly related to the amount of element within the XPS sampling volume.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] To generate atomic percentage values, each raw XPS signal is corrected by dividing the intensity by a *relative sensitivity factor* (RSF), and normalized over all of the elements detected.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Since hydrogen is not detected, these atomic percentages exclude hydrogen.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] XPS is widely used to generate an empirical formula because it readily yields excellent quantitative accuracy from homogeneous solid-state materials.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Absolute quantification requires the use of certified (or independently verified) standard samples, and is generally more challenging, and less common.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Relative quantification involves comparisons between several samples in a set for which one or more analytes are varied while all other components (the sample matrix) are held constant.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Under optimal conditions, the quantitative accuracy of the atomic percent (at%) values calculated from the major XPS peaks is 90–95% for each peak.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The quantitative accuracy for the weaker XPS signals, that have peak intensities 10–20% of the strongest signal, are 60–80% of the true value, and depend upon the amount of effort used to improve the signal-to-noise ratio (for example by signal averaging).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Quantitative precision (the ability to repeat a measurement and obtain the same result) is an essential consideration for proper reporting of quantitative results.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Detection limits may vary greatly with the cross section of the core state of interest and the background signal level.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] In general, photoelectron cross sections increase with atomic number.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The background increases with the atomic number of the matrix constituents as well as the binding energy, because of secondary emitted electrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] For example, in the case of gold on silicon where the high cross section Au4f peak is at a higher kinetic energy than the major silicon peaks, it sits on a very low background and detection limits of 1ppm or better may be achieved with reasonable acquisition times.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Conversely for silicon on gold, where the modest cross section Si2p line sits on the large background below the Au4f lines, detection limits would be much worse for the same acquisition time.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Detection limits are often quoted as 0.1–1.0 % atomic percent (0.1% = 1 part per thousand = 1000 ppm) for practical analyses, but lower limits may be achieved in many circumstances.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Degradation depends on the sensitivity of the material to the wavelength of X-rays used, the total dose of the X-rays, the temperature of the surface and the level of the vacuum.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Metals, alloys, ceramics and most glasses are not measurably degraded by either non-monochromatic or monochromatic X-rays.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Some, but not all, polymers, catalysts, certain highly oxygenated compounds, various inorganic compounds and fine organics are.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Non-monochromatic X-ray sources produce a significant amount of high energy Bremsstrahlung X-rays (1–15 keV of energy) which directly degrade the surface chemistry of various materials.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Non-monochromatic X-ray sources also produce a significant amount of heat (100 to 200 °C) on the surface of the sample because the anode that produces the X-rays is typically only 1 to 5 cm (2 in) away from the sample.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] This level of heat, when combined with the Bremsstrahlung X-rays, acts to increase the amount and rate of degradation for certain materials.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Monochromatised X-ray sources, because they are farther away (50–100 cm) from the sample, do not produce noticeable heat effects.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] In those, a quartz monochromator system diffracts the Bremsstrahlung X-rays out of the X-ray beam, which means the sample is only exposed to one narrow band of X-ray energy.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] For example, if aluminum K-alpha X-rays are used, the intrinsic energy band has a FWHM of 0.43 eV, centered on 1,486.7 eV (*E*/Δ*E* = 3,457).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] If magnesium K-alpha X-rays are used, the intrinsic energy band has a FWHM of 0.36 eV, centered on 1,253.7 eV (*E*/Δ*E* = 3,483).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] These are the intrinsic X-ray line widths; the range of energies to which the sample is exposed depends on the quality and optimization of the X-ray monochromator.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Because the vacuum removes various gases (e.g., O2, CO) and liquids (e.g., water, alcohol, solvents, etc.) that were initially trapped within or on the surface of the sample, the chemistry and morphology of the surface will continue to change until the surface achieves a steady state.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] This type of degradation is sometimes difficult to detect.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Measured area depends on instrument design.
