[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The time to complete a measurement is generally dependent on the brilliance of the X-ray source.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] XPS detects only electrons that have actually escaped from the sample into the vacuum of the instrument.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] In order to escape from the sample, a photoelectron must travel through the sample.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Photo-emitted electrons can undergo inelastic collisions, recombination, excitation of the sample, recapture or trapping in various excited states within the material, all of which can reduce the number of escaping photoelectrons.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] These effects appear as an exponential attenuation function as the depth increases, making the signals detected from analytes at the surface much stronger than the signals detected from analytes deeper below the sample surface.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Thus, the signal measured by XPS is an exponentially surface-weighted signal, and this fact can be used to estimate analyte depths in layered materials.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The ability to produce chemical state information, i.e. the local bonding environment of an atomic species in question from the topmost few nanometers of the sample makes XPS a unique and valuable tool for understanding the chemistry of the surface.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The local bonding environment is affected by the formal oxidation state, the identity of its nearest-neighbor atoms, and its bonding hybridization to the nearest-neighbor or next-nearest-neighbor atoms.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] For example, while the nominal binding energy of the C1*s* electron is 284.6 eV, subtle but reproducible shifts in the actual binding energy, the so-called *chemical shift* (analogous to NMR spectroscopy), provide the chemical state information.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Chemical-state analysis is widely used for carbon.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Chemical state analysis of the surface of a silicon wafer reveals chemical shifts due to different formal oxidation states, such as: n-doped silicon and p-doped silicon (metallic silicon), silicon suboxide (Si2O), silicon monoxide (SiO), Si2O3, and silicon dioxide (SiO2).
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] An example of this is seen in the figure "High-resolution spectrum of an oxidized silicon wafer in the energy range of the Si 2*p* signal".
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The most prevalent electron spectrometer for XPS is the hemispherical electron analyzer.
