[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] A breakthrough has been brought about in the last decades by the development of large scale synchrotron radiation facilities.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Here, bunches of relativistic electrons kept in orbit inside a storage ring are accelerated through bending magnets or insertion devices like wigglers and undulators to produce a high brilliance and high flux photon beam.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The beam is orders of magnitude more intense and better collimated than typically produced by anode-based sources.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Synchrotron radiation is also tunable over a wide wavelength range, and can be made polarized in several distinct ways.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] This way, photon can be selected yielding optimum photoionization cross-sections for probing a particular core level.
