[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] During this period it was found that small shifts in the nitride composition of the transistor gate resulted in undesirable shifts to the electrical properties of the devices being manufactured.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] XPS metrology tools designed to be used in the factory during the processing of the wafers are well suited for the measurement and control of the composition of these SiON films.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] By the 65 nm process node high-κ materials were being used regularly in the semiconductor industry and XPS tooling in the factory became more commonplace to add capability compared with traditional optical techniques.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] While inline semiconductor XPS metrology tools share the same basic principles as their laboratory based counterparts, these automated tools are more limited in functionality and capability.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] These tools do not have the ability to adjust the beam angle, and the beam size is reduced to enable the measurement to take place on small test structures on the wafer, further reducing the intensity available.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] More recent iterations of inline semiconductor XPS tools have begun to incorporate a secondary X-ray fluorescence (XRF) detector to enable the measurement of films which would normally be too thick for traditional XPS tooling.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Because XPS tools generate X-rays with an Aluminum source, these are considered low energy XRF tools, and are therefore not as capable as the heavy element sources found in traditional XRF tooling both in terms of total depth penetration as well as which materials are possible to measure.
