[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Charge induced shifting is normally due to a modest excess of low voltage (−1 to −20 eV) electrons attached to the surface, or a modest shortage of electrons (+1 to +15 eV) within the top 1–12 nm of the sample caused by the loss of photo-emitted electrons.
