[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Charge referencing is performed by adding a *Charge Correction* to each of the experimentally measured peaks.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Since various hydrocarbon species appear on all air-exposed surfaces, the binding energy of the hydrocarbon C (1s) XPS peak is used for the charge correction of all energies obtained from non-conductive samples or conductors that have been deliberately insulated from the sample mount.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The peak is normally found between 284.5 eV and 285.5 eV.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] The 284.8 eV binding energy is routinely used as the reference energy for charge referencing insulators, so that the charge correction is the difference between 284.8 eV and the experimentally measured C (1s) peak position.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Conductive materials and most native oxides of conductors should never need charge referencing.
[src:x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy/x-ray-photoelectron-spectroscopy] Conductive materials should never be charge referenced unless the topmost layer of the sample has a thick non-conductive film.
